item.title: Putin Critic Poisoned With Novichok, Berlin Says
item.description: Alexei Navalny was poisoned with the chemical nerve agent Novichok, the German government said, presenting the strongest evidence yet that the attack could have been carried out by Russian state agents.

item.title: France's Macron Pledges Support to Iraq Against Islamic State as U.S. Cuts Presence
item.description: French President Emmanuel Macron pledged support to Iraq’s new government in its fight against Islamic State as the U.S. cuts its troop presence.

item.title: Charlie Hebdo Trial Begins Five Years After Terrorist Attacks
item.description: The alleged accomplices of the terror attacks on Charlie Hebdo and a kosher grocery store went on trial Wednesday, a day after the satirical magazine republished cartoons of the Prophet Muhammad that triggered the attackers five years ago.

item.title: 'They Called Me 'Slave': Beirut Blast Exposes Migrant Workers' Plight
item.description: Covid-19 and an economic collapse in Lebanon following the deadly explosion last month reveal the inequities of a labor system at the heart of Mideast economies, including confiscated passports.

item.title: Inside Russia's Race to Develop a Covid-19 Vaccine Before the West
item.description: President Vladimir Putin pressured his top scientists to do what they could to develop a coronavirus vaccine. But his political victory in becoming the first global leader to announce the approval of one drew skepticism from experts and politicians around the world.

item.title: Australia Falls Into Recession for the First Time in Nearly Three Decades
item.description: Australia’s first recession in 29 years was confirmed when data showed the economy contracted by a record 7% in the three months through June—it marked the end of the longest-running growth streak in the developed world.
